	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>The EU, fisheries agreements and sub-regional cooperation in west Africa</h1>

			
			<h4>
												31 March 2005
										</h4>

					</header>


				<div class="intro">

						<p> The EU is allocating euros 14 million (through its development co-operation policy, via the regional indicative programme for west Africa) to finance support programmes for fisheries policy in the region.</p>

		</div>
		
		
					<p> This was announced in a press conference in Dakar for the 20th anniversary of the sub-regional fisheries committee (SRFC), by Mr Deben (DG Fisheries) in early April 2005. Complementary support from the CFP will be allocated for fisheries research in the region.</p><p> The first part of the funding (about euros 5 million) will be used for the reinforcement of regional capacity for control and surveillance, while the second part will be used to reinforce national capacities. Mr Deben explained that these funds are independent of fisheries agreements, but complementary. He stated that decreasing fishing effort in the region is of paramount importance for sustainable management of resources. He also said that the EU was determined to support a regional approach to future agreements negotiations.</p><p>
 During the press conference, Mr Deben blamed the Senegalese artisanal fishing sector for pillaging Senegalese resources. This prompted a response by Mr Djibo Kâ, minister of the maritime economy and also president of the SRFC council of ministers, who described these assertions as 'excessive'. The Senegalese government is in the process of organising a census of pirogues with a view to registering them in order to ensure that artisanal fishermen are properly controlled. Mr Kâ said Senegal is also undertaking a census of the industrial fishing sector and is planning to buy several patrol boats to ensure proper surveillance and control in the Senegal EEZ. For all these efforts, 'Senegal should have been congratulated by the EU' said Mr Kâ. A letter of encouragement was subsequently sent by the EC.<br/> </p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
<a href="http://www.africatime.com/burundi/nouv_pana.asp?no_nouvelle=181947&amp;no_categorie=3" target="_self">Press article in <i>Africa Time</i>, April 6th 2005</a> </p><p>
<a href="http://www.africatime.com/senegal/nouvelle.asp?no_nouvelle=182319&amp;no_categorie=3" target="_self">Press article in <i>Africa Time</i>, April 7th 2005</a> </p><p>
<a href="http://fr.allafrica.com/stories/200504110867.html" target="_self">Article by Wal Fadjri in <i>allAfrica.com</i>, April 11th 2005</a> </p><p>

<a href="http://www.africatime.com/senegal/nouvelle.asp?no_nouvelle=182882&amp;no_categorie=3" target="_self">Press article in <i> Le Quotidien</i>, April 11th 2005</a> <br/> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> Several aspects of this interaction between the EC representative, the SRFC and the Senegalese authorities are of wider interest for ACP countries.</p><p> First of all, the fact that DG Fisheries was the EC department to announce that the financial support is to be through the EU's Cooperation and Development RIP is not without significance. It shows how 'coherence' between fisheries and development is likely to be implemented, with a strong lead to be taken by DG fisheries, and probably therefore by EU fisheries interests. The fact that funds channelled through the European CFP are presented as 'complementary' to the development funds, shows that the EU, and DG fisheries in particular, wish to present FPAs, which are a tool of the CFP, as a complementary 'development tool'. This may provide an opportunity for ACP countries to base FPA negotiations on the ACP's own sustainable development challenges, such as the sustainable exploitation of resources, job creation, the need for operations adding value to be based in ACP countries, etc.</p><p> There is a risk, however, that DG Fish will interfere with the way that ACP countries are managing their fisheries sectors, and will push for the ACP national (small-scale in this case) sector to be the one in which the fishing effort should be reduced. This may lead to a situation in which, in the case of fully exploited resources, EU fleets, under the guise of FPAs, are given priority access over national, often small-scale operators. ACP countries must resist this, particularly given the important contribution that small-scale fisheries can make to achieving the 'Millennium Goals'.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
	</article>

